From: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
Date: Wed, 27 May 2026 17:50:30 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] mm/damon/reclaim: handle ctx allocation failure

DAMON_RECLAIM allocates its damon_ctx object in its init function.  If
the allocation fails, damon_reclaim_enabled_store() could dereference
the NULL pointer.  Fix by checking if the previous allocation is failed,
and retry the allocation in the case.

Note that this is slightly changing the module's behavior.  Before the
broken commit, writing 'Y' to 'enabled' always failed when the ctx
allocation in the init function is failed.   This commit makes it to
always retry the allocation.  It is hard to imagine users who depend on
the old behavior.  Also, the level of memory pressure that can make even
one damon_ctx allocation fails can reasonably be expected to be only
temporal.  Hence this behavioral change wouldn't break users but improve
the user experience.

Fixes: 3f7a914ab9a5 ("mm/damon/reclaim: use damon_initialized()")
Cc: <stable@vger.kernel.org> # 6.18.x
Signed-off-by: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
---
 mm/damon/reclaim.c | 7 +++++++
 1 file changed, 7 insertions(+)

diff --git a/mm/damon/reclaim.c b/mm/damon/reclaim.c
index ed446d00ef1cf..88f74b72d8902 100644
--- a/mm/damon/reclaim.c
+++ b/mm/damon/reclaim.c
@@ -399,6 +399,13 @@ static int damon_reclaim_enabled_store(const char *val,
 	if (!damon_initialized())
 		return 0;
 
+	/* init function's allocation could be failed. */
+	if (!ctx) {
+		err = damon_modules_new_paddr_ctx_target(&ctx, &target);
+		if (!err)
+			return -ENOMEM;
+	}
+
 	return damon_reclaim_turn(enabled);
 }
 
-- 
